        {"num": "Slide 2", "title": "Learning Objectives", "visual": "Learning goals and vocabulary terms", "say": "Today we're going to discover why one equation — written in 1903 — determines whether space mining is possible. And it's not what you'd expect.", "do": "Have students read objectives. Pre-teach 'delta-v' with the analogy: it's like the total budget of velocity changes your spacecraft can make, and every kilometer per second costs exponentially more fuel.", "time": "3 min"},
        {"num": "Slide 3", "title": "Big Question", "visual": "Asteroid worth $10 trillion — why not go get it?", "say": "Imagine finding a mountain of gold in your backyard — but it's at the bottom of a 100-mile-deep hole. The gold is real. The hole is the physics of getting to space.", "do": "Quick-write: Students estimate what it costs to launch 1 kg to space. Reveal: $2,700-$10,000. Calculate what a glass of water would cost in orbit ($5-10 per glass at those rates).", "time": "3 min"},
